  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"A True Story\", \"Based On A True Story\" and \"Inspired By A True Story\" in movies?",
  "response": "In movies, the phrases \"A True Story,\" \"Based on a True Story,\" and \"Inspired by a True Story\" are used to indicate the level of fidelity to real-life events. Here\u2019s a breakdown of what each typically means:\n\n1. **\"A True Story\"**:\n   - This implies that the movie is a faithful representation of real events, with a high degree of accuracy in portraying the facts, characters, and timeline.\n   - However, even in these cases, filmmakers often take some creative liberties for dramatic effect, character development, or pacing, so complete historical accuracy is rare.\n\n2. **\"Based on a True Story\"**:\n   - This suggests that the movie is rooted in real events but has undergone significant dramatization or alteration for storytelling purposes.\n   - Key elements of the story may be true, but characters, events, dialogue, or timelines might be altered, combined, or fictionalized to enhance the narrative.\n\n3. **\"Inspired by a True Story\"**:\n   - This indicates that the movie takes loose inspiration from real events or people but is largely a work of fiction.\n   - The connection to reality might be minimal, with only a kernel of truth serving as the foundation for a primarily fictionalized story.\n\nIn summary, the terms represent a sliding scale of adherence to factual accuracy, from closest to the truth (\"A True Story\") to loosely connected (\"Inspired by a True Story\"). Always remember that filmmakers prioritize storytelling over strict historical accuracy, even in the most \"faithful\" adaptations.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
